As part of our larger network, HCA Healthcare, we are committed to reducing health disparities and advancing health equity. In 2021, we formed the HCA Healthcare Health Equity Council to identify and address health disparities both within and beyond the walls of our hospitals. A critical piece of this strategy is partnering with organizations like March of Dimes to improve maternal health for communities of color. On Thursday, April 21 at 2 p.m. ET, March of Dimes will host the next installation of the Healthy Moms, Strong Babies webinar series. Join a panel of experts as they discuss the relationship between women of color and systemic racism with the healthcare system. Isabella Abbott was a Hawaiian algae expert who completed important research in botany. She taught marine botany at Stanford‚Äôs Hopkins Marine station between 1960 and 1982. She was the first female professor as well as the first Asian professor at Stanford. She also was one of the first professors to study and teach Hawaiian ethnobotany. In 1997, she was awarded the Gilbert Morgan Smith medal, which is the most significant award in marine botany, from the National Academy of Sciences. Steven Chu was a Chinese American who was the first Asian American to serve as the Secretary of Energy. He was a co-recipient of the Novel Prize for Physics in 1997 and worked for many years to develop renewable technologies at the Lawrence Berkeley National Lab. He completed important research regarding atom interferometry, the study of polymers, and quantum electronics. Like and share this post if you learned something today! #mfl #myfirstlab

Black men are just as human as everyone else. They feel a range of emotions, dream of living a good life, and experience ups and downs ‚Äî yet, they‚Äôre not always supported in expressing their feelings. Because society enforces the idea that men must neglect their emotional and mental well-being to be considered ‚Äúmanly,‚Äù many Black men suffer in silence. Or worse, with Black men being four times more likely to commit suicide than Black women, they die without receiving the care they deserve. ‚ÄúWhat ends up happening for most Black males is that we start to internalize that pain,‚Äù says Brandon Jones, a psychotherapist who specializes in intergenerational trauma and adverse childhood experiences. #TheAtlantaVoice #MentalHealth #BlackMentalHealthMatters

The Atlanta Braves and 7G Foundation will host the first ever Native American All-Star Baseball Showcase at Truist Park, July 16-17, 2022. The top 50 high school baseball players of Native American descent from around the country will participate in a pro-style workout on Saturday, July 16 and a showcase game on Sunday, July 17. PROUD MEMBER HIGHLIGHT! We are excited to feature our extraordinary member Jane Velez-Mitchell this week. She is a friend, a board member of Rowdy Girl, and my sister from another mother!! Learn more about Jane's fantastic work and how she makes a difference for animals worldwide. JANE‚ÄôS WHY "I'm a member of the Rowdy Girl Sanctuary because it provides the roadmap to saving the planet from climate apocalypse! I am a pro-farmer and know many of them hate modern-day animal agriculture's cruel and destructive system and want to work the land without killing! There is a better way, and Renee and Tommy Sonnen's sanctuary offers that blueprint. They are ranchers who have pioneered that more innovative, kinder way and teach others how to do it. For everyone's benefit, the animals, people, and the planet, we should all join Rowdy Girl Sanctuary! And, it's fun! Hoedowns and tours and talks! Come on and join us." - Jane Velez-Mitchell Jane Velez-Mitchell is the founder and content editor of JaneUnChained, a multi-platform social media news outlet that produces original video content on animal welfare and the compassionate lifestyle. And recently launched UNCHAINED TV live streaming app. For six years, she hosted her own show on HLN/CNN Headline News, where she ran a weekly segment on animal issues that consistently broke the news. Previously, Velez-Mitchell reported for the nationally syndicated Warner Brothers/Telepictures show Celebrity Justice, where she did numerous stories on animal issues championed by celebrities. Previously, Velez-Mitchell was a news anchor/reporter at KCAL-TV in Los Angeles and WCBS-TV in New York. By becoming a PROUD member, you will help us provide them with food, shelter, vet care, and the constant improvement of their quality of life. Are you interested in learning more about conservation efforts in South Dakota? Take a look at our two-part Conservation Class, happening this Saturday, January 29. Part 1 of this introductory course will discuss the basics of conservation and what conservation looks like in South Dakota. Part 2 of this introductory class will review the basics of conservation and how it looks in South Dakota. We will go more in-depth on conservation by explaining and presenting some research on disappearing wetlands and how this will affect waterfowl populations. On this last day of #blackhistorymonth we would like to honor our very own Malika Redmond the CEO and co-founder of #WomenEngaged. Malika Redmond is the co-founder and CEO of Women Engaged a nonprofit based in Atlanta, GA, that works to inspire Black women and young adults to become impactful leaders, key decision-makers and effective agents for social change through voter engagement and reproductive justice advocacy and leadership development. Malika has worked for 20 years both nationally and internationally managing projects that focus on women's human rights, racial justice, and youth empowerment. She founded the International Black Youth Summit in 1994, and was one of the youngest national field organizers for the 2004 March for Women‚Äôs Lives an event that brought nearly 1 million participants to the National Mall. Malika served two elected terms as the 1st board Chair of the ProGeorgia Civic Engagement Table, and first leader of a Reproductive Justice organization to do so. Her awards include the 2016 distinguished Rockwood Leadership Institute for Leaders In the Reproductive Health, Rights, and Justice field,"Stand Up for Reproductive Justice" award by Feminist Women's Health Center, "Legends in the Making" award by Planned Parenthood, SE, and a nominated "ChangeMaker" for the 2016 United States of Women conference. Her writings are featured in Truthout, Blavity, Essence, and AlterNet. Malika holds a BA from Spelman College and MA from Georgia State University. We celebrate you üíú‚úäüèæ #WomenEngaged #WeVoteWeRise #blackhistorymonth

SNEAK PEEK ALERT üòç We have a recipe to get you excited for The Van Life Cookbook by Susan Marque! Try this delicious Van Life Summer Rolls recipe. You'll Need: ‚Ä¢4 small Vietnamese rice wrap sheets ‚Ä¢fresh basil leaves ‚Ä¢4 slices of feta (vegan or regular) ‚Ä¢1 carrot, washed and cut into matchstick pieces ‚Ä¢1 small zucchini, washed and cut into matchstick pieces Instructions: 1. Heat about 1 inch of water in a fry pan until hot but not boiling. 2. Turn off the heat under the pan. 3. Place 1 rice wrap sheet into the water to soften. (Give it a few seconds.) 4. Carefully put the wrap on a cutting board. 5. Put 1 large or several tiny basil leaves in the middle of the wrap. 6. Put a slice of feta on top of the basil. 7. Put a few carrots and a few zucchini pieces on top of the cheese. 8. Fold in the sides of the wrap to cover the ingredients like a tiny burrito. 9. Repeat softening and filling the wraps until all the filling is used up, to make 4 rolls. Make sure you check out her new cookbook ü•ò: http://ow.ly/EQPg50I66L3:=:https://ulyssespress.com/books/the-van-life-cookbook/

Architect Mary Coulter was a Saint Paul-born designer and architect. Although famous for her iconic buildings at the Grand Canyon, her story has been somewhat overlooked. Mary was born in Pittsburgh in 1869 to Irish immigrant parents who moved around somewhat until settling in St. Paul when she was eleven. These moves and the time her family spent in Colorado and Texas may have influenced Mary‚Äôs style and her love of Native American art. Mary graduated from Central High School at only fourteen, then went to California for college. She returned to St. Paul to teach drawing literature and other subjects at Mechanic Arts High School for fifteen years, helping to build the school into an important center for the Arts & Crafts Movement. She was then hired to design buildings and interiors for the Fred Harvey Company at the Grand Canyon. Influenced by her passion and respect of Native American art and culture, these buildings are now on the National Register of Historic Places, and are some of the most iconic buildings that grace our National Parks. Also an artist in her own right, Mary became known for skill and design in Arts & Crafts style metalworking. Even after moving to Kansas City, Mary Coulter retained close ties to Minnesota, teaching at the University of Minnesota-Extension, setting up exhibitions, and reviewing books and staying in touch with friends, including former Mechanic Arts principal George Weitbrecht. Mary Coulter died in 1958 at her house in Santa Fe. Image: Mary Colter (right) in about 1935, discussing plans for Bright Angel Lodge with Miner Tillotson (left), superintendent of the Grand Canyon National Park, and Anna W. Ickes, the wife of Harold Ickes, Franklin Roosevelt‚Äôs secretary of the Interior, and an advocate for the culture, archeology, and welfare of Native Americans. Photo courtesy of Grand Canyon National Park, #16942. From Ramsey County History magazine. For more on Mary Coulter, see the article by Diane Trout-Oertel at https://publishing.rchs.com/publishing/magazine/ramsey-county-history-magazine-volume-45-4-winter-2011/
